<para id="para-00036">Is the mean of the Final Exam scores of the online class lower than the mean of the Final Exam scores of the face-to-face class? Test at a 5% significance level. Use the 8-step process to guide the hypothesis test.</para>
</problem>
<solution id="sol-00003">
<para id="para-00037"><emphasis>1. Type of test:</emphasis> This is a test of two independent group means with population standard deviations unknown.</para>
<para id="para-00038"><emphasis>2. Hypotheses:</emphasis> Let <m:math><m:mi>o</m:mi><m:mo>=</m:mo></m:math> the subscript for the online class and <m:math><m:mi>f</m:mi><m:mo>=</m:mo></m:math> the subscript for the face-to-face class. The words “lower than” translate to a “&lt;” symbol, which goes into the alternative hypothesis. The test is left-tailed.</para>
<equation class="unnumbered" id="eq-00008">
<m:math><m:msub><m:mi>H</m:mi><m:mrow><m:mn>0</m:mn></m:mrow></m:msub><m:mo>:</m:mo><m:msub><m:mi>μ</m:mi><m:mrow><m:mi>o</m:mi></m:mrow></m:msub><m:mo>≥</m:mo><m:msub><m:mi>μ</m:mi><m:mrow><m:mi>f</m:mi></m:mrow></m:msub></m:math>
</equation><equation class="unnumbered" id="eq-00009">
<m:math><m:msub><m:mi>H</m:mi><m:mrow><m:mi>a</m:mi></m:mrow></m:msub><m:mo>:</m:mo><m:msub><m:mi>μ</m:mi><m:mrow><m:mi>o</m:mi></m:mrow></m:msub><m:mo>&lt;</m:mo><m:msub><m:mi>μ</m:mi><m:mrow><m:mi>f</m:mi></m:mrow></m:msub></m:math>
</equation>
<para id="para-00039"><emphasis>3. Random Variable:</emphasis> <m:math><m:msub><m:mrow><m:mover><m:mrow><m:mi>X</m:mi></m:mrow><m:mo accent="true">―</m:mo></m:mover></m:mrow><m:mrow><m:mi>o</m:mi></m:mrow></m:msub><m:mo>−</m:mo><m:msub><m:mrow><m:mover><m:mrow><m:mi>X</m:mi></m:mrow><m:mo accent="true">―</m:mo></m:mover></m:mrow><m:mrow><m:mi>f</m:mi></m:mrow></m:msub><m:mo>=</m:mo></m:math> the difference in the sample mean final exam scores of the online class and the face-to-face class.</para>
<para id="para-00040"><emphasis>4. Distribution:</emphasis> Student’s <m:math><m:mi>t</m:mi></m:math>-distribution with <m:math><m:mtext>df</m:mtext><m:mo>≈</m:mo><m:mn>51.6087</m:mn></m:math> (calculated with a calculator or computer; do not pool the variances). From the sample data: <m:math><m:msub><m:mrow><m:mover><m:mrow><m:mi>x</m:mi></m:mrow><m:mo accent="true">―</m:mo></m:mover></m:mrow><m:mrow><m:mi>o</m:mi></m:mrow></m:msub><m:mo>=</m:mo><m:mn>72.85</m:mn></m:math>, <m:math><m:msub><m:mi>s</m:mi><m:mrow><m:mi>o</m:mi></m:mrow></m:msub><m:mo>≈</m:mo><m:mn>16.92</m:mn></m:math>, <m:math><m:msub><m:mi>n</m:mi><m:mrow><m:mi>o</m:mi></m:mrow></m:msub><m:mo>=</m:mo><m:mn>30</m:mn></m:math>, and <m:math><m:msub><m:mrow><m:mover><m:mrow><m:mi>x</m:mi></m:mrow><m:mo accent="true">―</m:mo></m:mover></m:mrow><m:mrow><m:mi>f</m:mi></m:mrow></m:msub><m:mo>=</m:mo><m:mn>84.98</m:mn></m:math>, <m:math><m:msub><m:mi>s</m:mi><m:mrow><m:mi>f</m:mi></m:mrow></m:msub><m:mo>≈</m:mo><m:mn>11.71</m:mn></m:math>, <m:math><m:msub><m:mi>n</m:mi><m:mrow><m:mi>f</m:mi></m:mrow></m:msub><m:mo>=</m:mo><m:mn>30</m:mn></m:math>. The standard error is <m:math><m:mi>S</m:mi><m:mi>E</m:mi><m:mo>=</m:mo><m:msqrt><m:mrow><m:mfrac><m:mrow><m:msup><m:mrow><m:mn>16.92</m:mn></m:mrow><m:mrow><m:mn>2</m:mn></m:mrow></m:msup></m:mrow><m:mrow><m:mn>30</m:mn></m:mrow></m:mfrac><m:mo>+</m:mo><m:mfrac><m:mrow><m:msup><m:mrow><m:mn>11.71</m:mn></m:mrow><m:mrow><m:mn>2</m:mn></m:mrow></m:msup></m:mrow><m:mrow><m:mn>30</m:mn></m:mrow></m:mfrac></m:mrow></m:msqrt><m:mo>≈</m:mo><m:mn>3.7571</m:mn></m:math>.</para>
<para id="para-00041"><emphasis>5. Test Statistic:</emphasis> <m:math><m:mi>t</m:mi><m:mo>=</m:mo><m:mfrac><m:mrow><m:mn>72.85</m:mn><m:mo>−</m:mo><m:mn>84.98</m:mn></m:mrow><m:mrow><m:mn>3.7571</m:mn></m:mrow></m:mfrac><m:mo>≈</m:mo><m:mo>−</m:mo><m:mn>3.23</m:mn></m:math>.</para>
<para id="para-00042"><emphasis>6. <m:math><m:mi>p</m:mi></m:math>-value:</emphasis> <m:math><m:mi>P</m:mi><m:mo stretchy="false">(</m:mo><m:mi>t</m:mi><m:mo>&lt;</m:mo><m:mo>−</m:mo><m:mn>3.23</m:mn><m:mo stretchy="false">)</m:mo><m:mo>≈</m:mo><m:mn>0.0011</m:mn></m:math>. If <m:math><m:msub><m:mi>H</m:mi><m:mrow><m:mn>0</m:mn></m:mrow></m:msub></m:math> is true, there is a 0.0011 probability (0.11%) that the online class’s sample mean is 12.13 points or more below the face-to-face class’s sample mean.</para>
<para id="para-00043"><emphasis>7. Graph:</emphasis> The graph of this situation is below, on Student’s <m:math><m:mi>t</m:mi></m:math>-distribution with <m:math><m:mtext>df</m:mtext><m:mo>≈</m:mo><m:mn>51.6087</m:mn></m:math>.</para>
<figure id="fs-idm98197120">
<media alt="Student's t-distribution centered at 0 with the region to the left of t = -3.23 shaded; the shaded area equals the p-value of 0.0011.">
<image mime-type="image/png" src="../../media/CNX_Stats_C10_s2_img3.png"/>
</media>
</figure>
<para id="para-00044"><emphasis>8. Decision and Conclusion:</emphasis> Compare <m:math><m:mi>α</m:mi></m:math> and the <m:math><m:mi>p</m:mi></m:math>-value: <m:math><m:mi>α</m:mi><m:mo>=</m:mo><m:mn>0.05</m:mn></m:math> and <m:math><m:mi>p</m:mi></m:math>-value <m:math><m:mo>≈</m:mo><m:mn>0.0011</m:mn></m:math>, so <m:math><m:mi>α</m:mi><m:mo>></m:mo></m:math> <m:math><m:mi>p</m:mi></m:math>-value. Reject <m:math><m:msub><m:mi>H</m:mi><m:mrow><m:mn>0</m:mn></m:mrow></m:msub></m:math>. At the 5% level of significance, from the sample data, there is sufficient evidence to conclude that the mean final exam score of the online class is lower than the mean final exam score of the face-to-face class. The professor was correct.</para>
</solution>
</exercise>
</example>
<note id="fs-idm11616112" class="statistics calculator">
<title>Using the TI-83, 83+, 84, 84+ Calculator</title>
<para id="para-00045">First put the data for each group into two lists (such as L1 and L2). Press <code>STAT</code>. Arrow over to <code>TESTS</code> and press <code>4:2-SampTTest</code>. Make sure Data is highlighted and press <code>ENTER</code>. Arrow down and enter <code>L1</code> for the first list and <code>L2</code> for the second list. Arrow down to <m:math><m:msub><m:mi>μ</m:mi><m:mrow><m:mn>1</m:mn></m:mrow></m:msub></m:math>: and arrow to <code>&lt;</code> <m:math><m:msub><m:mi>μ</m:mi><m:mrow><m:mn>2</m:mn></m:mrow></m:msub></m:math> (less than). Press <code>ENTER</code>. Arrow down to Pooled: No. Press <code>ENTER</code>. Arrow down to <code>Calculate</code> and press <code>ENTER</code>.</para>
</note>
<note id="fs-idm107478368" class="statistics note">
<title>NOTE</title>
<para id="para-00046">Be careful not to mix up the information for Group 1 and Group 2!</para>
</note>
<note id="note-00001" class="statistics try">
<title>Try It</title>
<exercise id="exer-00006">
<problem id="prob-00006">
<para id="para-00047">Two professors, A and B, teach classes on the same subjects. Scores of 10 students from each class are selected randomly. The final exam scores of the students are as follows:</para>
<para id="para-00048">Professor A:</para>
<table id="table-00001" summary="This table contains the ten final exam scores for Professor A’s class in two rows of five values.">
<tgroup cols="5">
<colspec colnum="1" colname="c1"/>
<colspec colnum="2" colname="c2"/>
<colspec colnum="3" colname="c3"/>
<colspec colnum="4" colname="c4"/>
<colspec colnum="5" colname="c5"/>
<tbody valign="top">
<row>
<entry>97</entry>
<entry>62</entry>
<entry>73</entry>
<entry>58</entry>
<entry>84</entry>
</row>
<row>
<entry>74</entry>
<entry>66</entry>
<entry>93</entry>
<entry>73</entry>
<entry>85</entry>
</row>
</tbody>
</tgroup>
</table>
<para id="para-00049">Professor B:</para>
<table id="table-00002" summary="This table contains the ten final exam scores for Professor B’s class in two rows of five values.">
<tgroup cols="5">
<colspec colnum="1" colname="c1"/>
<colspec colnum="2" colname="c2"/>
<colspec colnum="3" colname="c3"/>
<colspec colnum="4" colname="c4"/>
<colspec colnum="5" colname="c5"/>
<tbody valign="top">
<row>
<entry>85</entry>
<entry>64</entry>
<entry>74</entry>
<entry>55</entry>
<entry>76</entry>
</row>
<row>
<entry>67</entry>
<entry>72</entry>
<entry>84</entry>
<entry>71</entry>
<entry>98</entry>
</row>
</tbody>
</tgroup>
</table>
<para id="para-00050">Professor A says that the mean score of their class is more than the mean of professor B’s class. Is professor A correct? Test at a 5% significance level.</para>
</problem>
<solution id="sol-00004">
            <list list-type="enumerated" number-style="lower-alpha" id="list-00005">
            <item>two means</item>
            <item>unknown</item>
            <item>Student’s <m:math><m:mi>t</m:mi></m:math></item>
            <item>
              <m:math><m:msub><m:mrow><m:mover><m:mrow><m:mi>X</m:mi></m:mrow><m:mo accent="true">―</m:mo></m:mover></m:mrow><m:mrow><m:mn>1</m:mn></m:mrow></m:msub><m:mo>−</m:mo><m:msub><m:mrow><m:mover><m:mrow><m:mi>X</m:mi></m:mrow><m:mo accent="true">―</m:mo></m:mover></m:mrow><m:mrow><m:mn>2</m:mn></m:mrow></m:msub></m:math>
            </item>
            <item>
              <list list-type="enumerated" number-style="arabic" id="list-00006">
                <item><m:math><m:msub><m:mi>H</m:mi><m:mn>0</m:mn></m:msub><m:mo>:</m:mo><m:msub><m:mi>μ</m:mi><m:mn>1</m:mn></m:msub><m:mo>≤</m:mo><m:msub><m:mi>μ</m:mi><m:mn>2</m:mn></m:msub></m:math> Null hypothesis: the mean of final exam scores for professor A’s class is at most the mean for professor B’s class.</item>
                <item><m:math><m:msub><m:mi>H</m:mi><m:mi>a</m:mi></m:msub><m:mo>:</m:mo><m:msub><m:mi>μ</m:mi><m:mn>1</m:mn></m:msub><m:mo>></m:mo><m:msub><m:mi>μ</m:mi><m:mn>2</m:mn></m:msub></m:math> Alternative hypothesis: the mean of final exam scores for professor A’s class is more than the mean for professor B’s class.</item>
              </list>
            </item>
            <item>right-tailed</item>
            <item><m:math><m:mi>p</m:mi></m:math>-value = 0.3694</item>
            <item>Do not reject the null hypothesis.</item>
            <item>At the 5% level of significance, from the sample data, there is not sufficient evidence to conclude that the mean of final exam scores of the class of professor A is more than that of the class of professor B. Professor A’s claim is not supported.</item>
          </list>
        </solution>
</exercise>
</note>
<section id="sect-00002">
<title>Cohen’s Standards for Small, Medium, and Large Effect Sizes</title>
<para id="para-00051">Cohen’s <m:math><m:mi>d</m:mi></m:math> is a measure of effect size based on the differences between two means. Cohen’s <m:math><m:mi>d</m:mi></m:math>, named for United States statistician Jacob Cohen, measures the relative strength of the differences between the means of two populations based on sample data. The calculated value of effect size is then compared to Cohen’s standards of small, medium, and large effect sizes.</para>
<table id="fs-idp93235584" summary="This table gives the size of the effect in the first column and the corresponding value of d in the second column.">
<title>Cohen’s Standard Effect Sizes</title>
<tgroup cols="2">
<colspec colnum="1" colname="c1"/>
<colspec colnum="2" colname="c2"/>
<thead valign="top">
<row>
<entry align="center">Size of effect</entry>
<entry align="center"><m:math><m:mi>d</m:mi></m:math></entry>
</row>
</thead>
<tbody valign="top">
<row>
<entry>Small</entry>
<entry>0.2</entry>
</row>
<row>
<entry>Medium</entry>
<entry>0.5</entry>
</row>
<row>
<entry>Large</entry>
<entry>0.8</entry>
</row>
</tbody>
</tgroup>
</table>
<para id="para-00052">Cohen’s <m:math><m:mi>d</m:mi></m:math> is the measure of the difference between two means divided by the pooled standard deviation: <m:math><m:mi>d</m:mi><m:mo>=</m:mo><m:mfrac><m:mrow><m:msub><m:mrow><m:mover><m:mrow><m:mi>x</m:mi></m:mrow><m:mo accent="true">―</m:mo></m:mover></m:mrow><m:mrow><m:mn>1</m:mn></m:mrow></m:msub><m:mo>−</m:mo><m:msub><m:mrow><m:mover><m:mrow><m:mi>x</m:mi></m:mrow><m:mo accent="true">―</m:mo></m:mover></m:mrow><m:mrow><m:mn>2</m:mn></m:mrow></m:msub></m:mrow><m:mrow><m:msub><m:mi>s</m:mi><m:mrow><m:mi>p</m:mi><m:mi>o</m:mi><m:mi>o</m:mi><m:mi>l</m:mi><m:mi>e</m:mi><m:mi>d</m:mi></m:mrow></m:msub></m:mrow></m:mfrac></m:math> where <m:math><m:msub><m:mi>s</m:mi><m:mrow><m:mi>p</m:mi><m:mi>o</m:mi><m:mi>o</m:mi><m:mi>l</m:mi><m:mi>e</m:mi><m:mi>d</m:mi></m:mrow></m:msub><m:mo>=</m:mo><m:msqrt><m:mrow><m:mfrac><m:mrow><m:mrow><m:mo stretchy="true" fence="true" form="prefix">(</m:mo><m:msub><m:mi>n</m:mi><m:mrow><m:mn>1</m:mn></m:mrow></m:msub><m:mo>−</m:mo><m:mn>1</m:mn><m:mo stretchy="true" fence="true" form="postfix">)</m:mo></m:mrow><m:msubsup><m:mi>s</m:mi><m:mrow><m:mn>1</m:mn></m:mrow><m:mrow><m:mn>2</m:mn></m:mrow></m:msubsup><m:mo>+</m:mo><m:mrow><m:mo stretchy="true" fence="true" form="prefix">(</m:mo><m:msub><m:mi>n</m:mi><m:mrow><m:mn>2</m:mn></m:mrow></m:msub><m:mo>−</m:mo><m:mn>1</m:mn><m:mo stretchy="true" fence="true" form="postfix">)</m:mo></m:mrow><m:msubsup><m:mi>s</m:mi><m:mrow><m:mn>2</m:mn></m:mrow><m:mrow><m:mn>2</m:mn></m:mrow></m:msubsup></m:mrow><m:mrow><m:msub><m:mi>n</m:mi><m:mrow><m:mn>1</m:mn></m:mrow></m:msub><m:mo>+</m:mo><m:msub><m:mi>n</m:mi><m:mrow><m:mn>2</m:mn></m:mrow></m:msub><m:mo>−</m:mo><m:mn>2</m:mn></m:mrow></m:mfrac></m:mrow></m:msqrt></m:math></para>
<example id="fs-idm100194752">
<exercise id="exer-00007">
<problem id="prob-00007">
<para id="para-00053">Calculate Cohen’s <m:math><m:mi>d</m:mi></m:math> for <link target-id="element-968">Example 10.2</link>. Is the size of the effect small, medium, or large? Explain what the size of the effect means for this problem.</para>
</problem>
<solution id="sol-00005">
<para id="para-00054"><m:math><m:msub><m:mrow><m:mover><m:mrow><m:mi>x</m:mi></m:mrow><m:mo accent="true">―</m:mo></m:mover></m:mrow><m:mrow><m:mn>1</m:mn></m:mrow></m:msub><m:mo>=</m:mo><m:mn>4</m:mn></m:math>, <m:math><m:msub><m:mi>s</m:mi><m:mrow><m:mn>1</m:mn></m:mrow></m:msub><m:mo>=</m:mo><m:mn>1.5</m:mn></m:math>, <m:math><m:msub><m:mi>n</m:mi><m:mrow><m:mn>1</m:mn></m:mrow></m:msub><m:mo>=</m:mo><m:mn>11</m:mn></m:math></para>
<para id="para-00055"><m:math><m:msub><m:mrow><m:mover><m:mrow><m:mi>x</m:mi></m:mrow><m:mo accent="true">―</m:mo></m:mover></m:mrow><m:mrow><m:mn>2</m:mn></m:mrow></m:msub><m:mo>=</m:mo><m:mn>3.5</m:mn></m:math>, <m:math><m:msub><m:mi>s</m:mi><m:mrow><m:mn>2</m:mn></m:mrow></m:msub><m:mo>=</m:mo><m:mn>1</m:mn></m:math>, <m:math><m:msub><m:mi>n</m:mi><m:mrow><m:mn>2</m:mn></m:mrow></m:msub><m:mo>=</m:mo><m:mn>9</m:mn></m:math></para>
<para id="para-00056"><m:math><m:mi>d</m:mi><m:mo>=</m:mo><m:mn>0.384</m:mn></m:math></para>
<para id="para-00057">The effect is small because 0.384 is between Cohen’s value of 0.2 for small effect size and 0.5 for medium effect size. The size of the differences of the means for the two colleges is small relative to the variability in the data. (Effect size describes the magnitude of a difference; whether a difference is statistically significant is determined by the hypothesis test, not by <m:math><m:mi>d</m:mi></m:math>.)</para>
</solution>
</exercise>
</example>
<note id="note-00002" class="statistics try">
<title>Try It</title>
<exercise id="exer-00008">
<problem id="prob-00008">
<para id="para-00058">Calculate Cohen’s <m:math><m:mi>d</m:mi></m:math> for <link target-id="fs-idp145514592">Try It 10.2</link>. Is the size of the effect small, medium, or large? Explain what the size of the effect means for this problem.</para>
</problem>
<solution id="sol-00006">
          <para id="para-00059">
            <m:math><m:msub><m:mrow><m:mover><m:mrow><m:mi>x</m:mi></m:mrow><m:mo accent="true">―</m:mo></m:mover></m:mrow><m:mrow><m:mn>1</m:mn></m:mrow></m:msub><m:mo>=</m:mo><m:mn>5</m:mn></m:math>
            <m:math><m:msub><m:mi>s</m:mi><m:mn>1</m:mn></m:msub><m:mo>=</m:mo><m:mn>1</m:mn><m:mo>.</m:mo><m:mn>2</m:mn></m:math>
            <m:math><m:msub><m:mi>n</m:mi><m:mn>1</m:mn></m:msub><m:mo>=</m:mo><m:mn>15</m:mn></m:math>
          </para>
          <para id="para-00060">
            <m:math><m:msub><m:mrow><m:mover><m:mrow><m:mi>x</m:mi></m:mrow><m:mo accent="true">―</m:mo></m:mover></m:mrow><m:mrow><m:mn>2</m:mn></m:mrow></m:msub><m:mo>=</m:mo><m:mn>4.5</m:mn></m:math>
            <m:math><m:msub><m:mi>s</m:mi><m:mn>2</m:mn></m:msub><m:mo>=</m:mo><m:mn>0</m:mn><m:mo>.</m:mo><m:mn>8</m:mn></m:math>
            <m:math><m:msub><m:mi>n</m:mi><m:mn>2</m:mn></m:msub><m:mo>=</m:mo><m:mn>20</m:mn></m:math>
          </para>
          <para id="para-00061"><m:math><m:mi>d</m:mi><m:mo>=</m:mo><m:mn>0.505</m:mn></m:math></para>
          <para id="para-00062">The effect is medium because 0.505 is very close to Cohen’s value of 0.5 for medium effect size. The size of the differences of the means for the two companies is moderate relative to the variability in the data. (Effect size describes the magnitude of a difference; whether a difference is statistically significant is determined by the hypothesis test, not by <m:math><m:mi>d</m:mi></m:math>.)</para>
        </solution>
</exercise>
</note>
<example id="fs-idm112602048">
<exercise id="exer-00009">
<problem id="prob-00009">
<para id="para-00063">Calculate Cohen’s <m:math><m:mi>d</m:mi></m:math> for <link target-id="fs-idm22935408">Example 10.3</link>. Is the size of the effect small, medium, or large? Explain what the size of the effect means for this problem.</para>
</problem>
<solution id="sol-00007">
<para id="para-00064"><m:math><m:mi>d</m:mi><m:mo>=</m:mo><m:mn>0.834</m:mn></m:math>; Large, because 0.834 is greater than Cohen’s 0.8 for a large effect size. The size of the differences between the means of the Final Exam scores of online students and students in a face-to-face class is large, indicating a substantial difference in practical terms.</para>
</solution>
</exercise>
</example>
<note id="fs-idp145071264" class="statistics try">
<title>Try It</title>
<exercise id="exer-00010">
<problem id="prob-00010">
<para id="para-00065">Weighted alpha is a measure of risk-adjusted performance of stocks over a period of a year. A high positive weighted alpha signifies a stock whose price has risen while a small positive weighted alpha indicates an unchanged stock price during the time period. Weighted alpha is used to identify companies with strong upward or downward trends. The weighted alpha for the top 30 stocks of banks in the northeast and in the west as identified by Nasdaq on May 24, 2013 are listed in <link target-id="fs-idm242901296"/> and <link target-id="fs-idm167801152"/>, respectively.</para>
